Salafi is a bit of a red herring here. While contemporaneously
identified with Usama bin Laden, the movement itself is a sort of
recurrant reformist base in Islamic history; the ideal of returning to
the pious communities of Mecca and Medina in the time of the Prophet,
much as Luther dreamed of bypassing Augustine to reach the original
intent of the church fathers, and certain parties in black robes grope
at the constitution.

The /founders/ of Salafism, while widely unknown outside of Near East
Studies, would be viewed as perfectly nice people.

Salafism, in its modern form, was created by Sayyid Jamāl al-Dīn al-
Afghānī and his students Muhammad Abduh and Muhammad Rashid Rida.

Al-Afghani was anti-colonial and advocated a sort of pan-Islamist
modernism that would unite the lands of Islam in order to expel the
foreigners. He was accused of being involved in a plot that killed the
Shah, and in exchange for being kept out of Persian hands, he wrote
much of the Sultan Abdul Hamid II's Pan-Islamist program.

Abduh, his student, created the form of what we'd now call Salafiyyeh.
While it retains the initial anti-colonialism, it added the idea of
the Salafiyyeh, the pious forebears. In Abduh's reading at al-Azhar,
he argued that the Islamic forefathers were rational and flexible in
their approach to faith, and that the strictures of later generations
had produced a rigid sort of Islam that was unresponsive to modernism.
Islamic jurisprudence, he argued, could easily keep its core values
while adapting to modern life.

Rashid al-Rida's interpretation of Al-Afghani was less flexible than
Abduh's. It suggested that renewal lay in rejecting all things Western
and abandoning Sufism for pure Islam of the forebears.

These fertile strands of thought were popularized by Hassan al-Banna,
who founded the Muslim Brotherhood, favoring a mixture of Abduh and
Ridda and popularizing it throughout the region. In Iran, the idea was
picked up by Jalal Al-e Ahmad to build his idea of "Westoxification."

The downside is that the founders of Salifiyyeh were apostates to the
western regimes that ruled their countries at the time; though Egypt
allowed publication, it ghettozed Abduh and limited his potential to
become populist like the Islamic Brotherhood.

Here ends the lesson.

One possibility for an appealing Salafist would be Mohammed Naguib's
Egypt--see
http://tinyurl.com/2p3c5p

Naguib is a Kemal model nationalist, though rather more pragmatic--Ben
Ali's Tunisia on steroids. Jonathan suggested that he'd split the
"silly" part of the Ikhwan from the "Serious."

This produces the tame, regime sponsored Islamism of Taha Hussein. It
takes its lead from Mohammed Abduh, calling itself "Modernist Islamic
Salafism" and speaks to a broad, flexible, modernist society that
neither rejects its Islamic traditions nor is destroyed by Western
industrialization.

The less popular, more vulgar, tame opposition Ikhwan offers a
populist variation on that line.

At present, the Muslim Brotherhood and other Salafist parties hold
seats in the lower houses of parliament of several Gulf States. Give
it a while, and that'll be respectable; a cannier Sheikh of Bahrain in
the first generation might have been able to co-opt the Muslim
Brotherhood against the Shi'a.

Another way to create palatable modern Salafists would be to short-
circuit the Yemeni Civil War, or give Saudi Arabia rather different
leadership. I'll get to that tomorrow in a separate post.

