Also, depending on circumstances, it might be convenient to
present as a nice guy someone who deviates somewhat from the Standard
Model of Niceness. Uncle Joe in WWII would be an example.

Speaking of Uncle Joe, he went to some lengths to avoid or
at delay a war with the Germans, prefering to fight opponents who
were far weaker than he was. Suppose, and I guess this requires
an alt-Stalin, he looks at the Munich Agreement and thinks "The West
are morons. This guy isn't going to be satisfied until Germany reaches
the Urals, if then," and arranges a prophelactic attack on Germany.

I was going to say that this kills the Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact
but maybe it doesn't: a joint invasion of Poland would make a decent
cover to get Soviet forces in position to attack Germany (That is,
if Germany expects the SU to attack Poland, then troop movements are
not as alarming).

In this TL, the Soviets are not caught off-guard by
war with Germany (since they are the ones starting it) and since
the invasion of Poland has isolated Germany, the war goes in favour
of the Soviets. At the end, a friendly puppet government is installed
in Berlin and Soviet troops are at the border with France.

Hitler escapes. He could choose suicide (as in OTL) but
he doesn't. His first flight takes him to Spain, where Franco puts
him up.

Britain and France are understandably alarmed at the Red Menace
poised on the border of France. Now, prior to the Russo-German War,
Hitler was clearly a greater menace than Stalin but Hitler has been
deposed and is no more threatening than Napoleon in 1814. Opposing
Stalin is more important than pre-War unpleasantness. Some method of
unifying support for the Anti-Red Effort is needed.

It would be handy if there was a person who the public could
see as the face of Free Germany and well, there's a candidate handy
in Spain, the guy who saved Germany's economy before his experiment
was so cruelly destroyed by Stalin's sneak attack. Poland is unfortunate
but every nation has the occasional lapse in judgement.

Stalin really doesn't have any interest in conquering the rest
of Europe because assimilating Germany and Poland (and whatever else
he picked up on the road to Berlin) is going to take time. The border
between Red Europe and Free Europe becomes extremely well fortified
and Europe settled down for decades of peering fiercely at each other
over the barracades.

Hitler in this TL gets better health care and somewhat less
stress, dying in 1953 (one week after Stalin). By this point, he has been
the face of Free Germany for about a decade and he has proven to be at least
somewhat flexible in filling this role (I mean, a guy who starts off as
a police spy and ends up running the organization he was supposed to
spy on has to be at least somewhat adpatable). Kindly Uncle Addie is
still a virulent anti-semite but without the Holocaust, this is far
more acceptable. In any case, most of his speeches talk about the Evils
of Communism, which makes him a valuable tool for the Allies. As well,
there is reason to think the timing of his death isn't totally a coincidence
and that Reds engineered his sudden death (Not true but handy).

Of course, once the Slow War is over, people will look at Hitler
and wonder if they really want action dolls of this guy* on the shelves
but with most of the worst actions of Nazis butterflied away, his
reputation won't be nearly as dark as in OTL.

* I joke: they'd be of Otto Skorzeny, Agent of Freedom. He even appears
in an issue of Captain America.

